quran[14]{c,v,t}:
  18,84,"Indeed, We empowered him in the land and brought him all kinds of means."
  18,85,"So he pursued a certain course"
  18,86,"until, when he had reached the setting of the sun, he found it setting in a murky{1}spring, and found a people in its vicinity. We said, “O Zul-Qarnayn, you may either punish or else treat them kindly.”",footnotes:1:[Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Hafs and Ya’qub read it as: “…in a hot spring,”]
  18,87,"He said, “As for the one who has committed injustices, we will punish him, then he will be returned to his Lord and He will punish him with a dreadful punishment."
  18,88,"But as for the one who has attained faith and has acted righteously, then for him is the excellent<i>(reward) </i>as repayment{1}, and we will speak to him with ease regarding our command.”",footnotes:1:[Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer, Shu’ba and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…then for him is the repayment for the excellent (deed), and we will…”]
  18,89,"Then he pursued a course"
  18,90,"until, when he reached the rising of the sun, he found it rising on a people for whom We had provided no shelter from it."
  18,91,"So it was. And surely We encompassed what he had with knowledge."
  18,92,"Then he pursued a course"
  18,93,"until, when he reached the point separating the two barriers, he found beside them a people who could barely comprehend{1}any word.",footnotes:1:[Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…who could barely make others comprehend any word.”]
  18,94,"They said, “O Zul-Qarnayn, Gog and Magog are corrupting the land, so can we make for you a tribute on condition that you build a barrier between us and them?”"
  18,95,"He said, “What my Lord has empowered me with is better.<i>(Just) </i>assist me with<i>(man) </i>power, and I will set a barricade between you<sup>pl </sup>and them."
  18,96,"Bring me blocks of iron.” Then when he had leveled up between the two cliffs, he said, “Blow.” And having turned it into a fire, he said, “Bring me tar to pour over it.”"
  18,97,"So neither could they climb it, nor could they penetrate it."
